Leslie Venetz
posts.content:
3 scripts for January outreach so you can stop "just checking in." 



1. Direct, Assumptive

"You said you wanted to discuss [top priority] in January.

Is it better to schedule that call this week or next? "


2. Curious, Nurturing

"When we spoke in [month], you shared that [top priority] was important. You'd hope to accomplish [outcome] by [timeline].

How is it going?"


3. Sense check

"Wondering if January is still the right timeline for us to reconnect

The tentative agenda is [top priority], [COI/ROI outcome].

Should we keep that agenda or what's more urgent for you in 2025?"


 Which of these January follow-up emails do you think would work best for you?

#DigitalTwins 

There are several stages of a digital twin:
The Static Twin: Only a static visualisation.
The Detailed Twin: Linked with additional data.
The As-Built Twin: Reflects the actual implementation.
The Sensored Twin: Updated with real-time data from IoT sensors.
The Responsive Twin: Reflects responsive action in the physical twin.
The Adaptive Twin: Simulates scenarios semi-automatically.
The Intelligent Twin: Makes decisions fully autonomously.

posts.content:
If you're managing your agency and a side hustle, read this:

You've got a lot of passions. Your 9-5 friends admire you but don't understand you.

It feels good to be this ambitious, but that's just what you tell yourself.

It actually doesn't feel too good at all.

Here's a hard lesson I learned in the last 6 months:

The person who chases two rabbits catches neither.

And here's a perspective you haven't heard before:

You're running multiple businesses BECAUSE you're afraid.

You're too afraid that if you go all in on one, it'll fail.

Or too afraid that the great idea will be a missed opportunity if you don't do it right now.

Shift the fear.

Unless you've already hit your goal in one business, there is no reason to add another.

We only get the one life. You can be the one who's admirable but constantly stressed...

gaining a millimeter of progress in a dozen directions.

Or you can be the one who takes longer to decide what they want, then goes all in on that one thing...

so you can do less but better.

Don't be fooled by those doing more than you.

You're doing enough. It simply isn't focused.

Focus comes first. Success comes after.

P.S. You're 4-years-old again. What superhero costume you wearing?

comments.commentText: I completely agree with this. But I do think there is a healthy line between entrepreneurship and hobbies you are passionate about. I'd go crazy if I didn't roll in my Jiu Jitsu dojo 6 times a week Colby Wegter!
Focus truly is essential for achieving meaningful success.

posts.content:
I feel that AI will actually RAISE the baseline quality for content (not lower it)

Prior to AI there was just lots of low quality human-generated content.

Not there’s lots of low quality AI generated content, it’s not that much different.

AI helps people who aren’t great writers or creators level up much quicker.

They can eliminate creators block, mimic styles of top creators, get feedback quicker.

AI won’t make the best content creators worse, it will elevate the worse ones that want to get better.

The ones who are lazy and never put in the effort we’re going to do that with or without AI.

Stay rooted in His promises and let His divine protection bring you peace and confidence in every step of your journey.


With faith and boldness,
The Marvins.

posts.content:
When it comes to hiring, it's easy to get caught up in the allure of experience and technical skills. While they’re undoubtedly important, they’re not always the most crucial factors for long-term success. 

Hiring kind people with a positive attitude often outweighs hiring someone with years of experience but a negative or toxic mindset. Why? Because kindness and a positive outlook create a ripple effect throughout your organization. People who approach challenges with optimism inspire others to do the same, and they foster an environment where collaboration, creativity, and innovation thrive. 

A kind team member doesn’t just contribute technically—they build relationships, uplift their colleagues, and create a sense of community within the workplace. On the other hand, someone who brings negativity can drag down morale, making it harder for the team to reach their full potential.

While experience is valuable, it’s the character and attitude of a person that will ultimately shape your company’s culture and future success. 

When you hire for kindness and a positive mindset, you’re investing in a thriving, resilient work environment that encourages growth, learning, and collaboration. 

So, the next time you're looking to expand your team, remember: attitude over experience, kindness over negativity, and positivity over pessimism. It’s the key to building a truly great workplace!
